Upon completion of travel, if the employee feels unwell, he/ she must see a Doctor and findings should be reported to company bythe fastest means.B. Travel Documents, Tickets and Accommodation1. Confirm that your Passport is valid for at least 6 months and has at least 3 blank pages.2. Check that you have a valid air ticket.3. Confirm that you have a valid Visa/ Letter of Guarantee and/or OK to Board.4. Check before hand with airlines/ agent regarding the airport/ terminal that you will be flying from and to, including transit points.Check your flight schedule and the details of alternative flights where applicable.5. Are Hotel arrangements in place? Get the booking done before hand to avoid hassles and delays.6. In an emergency you may book tickets/ hotels/ transport on line through recognised travel websites such as7. Make two photocopies of all your travel documents in case of emergency or if your documents are lost or stolen. Leave one copywith a friend or relative at home. It is always a great idea to let at least one person know exactly where you will be staying and how tocontact you in an emergency. Carry the other copy with you stored separately from the originals.Documents to make copies of include:Passport ID page1. Foreign visa (if applicable)2. Itinerary3. Hotel confirmation4. Airline ticket5. Driver's license6. Credit cards brought on the trip7. C. Your Health1. Take all necessary precautions while traveling if the place has any recent history of any medical cases. If possible postpone thejourney. If not check for epidemic/ pandemic in the area. 2. If the epidemic/ pandemic spreads while person is in the affected area, all necessary precautions (quarantine, medical help) to betaken once he arrives back.3. Avoid eating at unhygienic places.4. If you take prescription medication:Pack enough to last your entire trip, including some extra in case you are unexpectedly delayed.1. Carry your medications in their original labeled containers, and pack them in your carry-on bag since checked baggage is occasionally lost or delayed.2. Ask your pharmacy or physician for the generic equivalent name of your prescriptions in case you need to purchase additional medication abroad.3. Get a letter from your physician in case you are questioned about your carry-on medication; some countries have strict restrictions on bringing prescription oreven non-prescription medications into the country without proper medical documentation. 4. D. Security1. You should be aware of and avoid Terrorist prone areas2. You should be alert to the possibility of a Political coup or local unrest causing unsafe situations for the foreigners in a country.3. Keep information about local police, local agent, and embassy.4. Keep abreast with latest happening in the world while traveling and get the travel advisory if present for the particular area. You canvisit the following websites for more information:E. Weather Conditions1. Severe weather conditions can make it difficult to travel.2. Take appropriate clothing for the prevailing weather in the place.3. Check the weather forecast beforehand for the place being visited.F. Local Transport/ Travel1. Get information about the local transport beforehand through internet or travel books. Use authorized/ certified means of transport.2. Keep some local currency as an emergency.3. Contact details of local agent/ and embassy to be available.4. Obtain Information about the place to be visited prior travel.5. Use only government authorized taxi’s/ launches for traveling.6. Always note the taxi number and if possible details of the driver (Similarly in the case of launches).7. Get the time table of trains/ buses beforehand to get to places on time.8. If you plan to drive overseas, you may need to obtain an International Driving Permit (IDP). Many countries do not recognize yournational driver’s licenses without an accompanying IDP, and it is illegal to drive without a valid license and insurance in most places.
